"van Vuuren D.P., Eickhout B., Lucas P.L., den Elzen M.G.J.","Long-term multi-gas scenarios to stabilise radiative forcing - Exploring costs and benefits within an integrated assessment framework",2006,"Energy Journal","27","SPEC. ISS. NOV.",,"201","233",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-40949094300&partnerID=40&md5=4c5bcd053dc808ebc46fc4563a0aab3c","Netherlands Environment Assessment Agency (MNP/RIVM), PO Box 303, 3720 BA Bilthoven, Netherlands","van Vuuren, D.P., Netherlands Environment Assessment Agency (MNP/RIVM), PO Box 303, 3720 BA Bilthoven, Netherlands; Eickhout, B., Netherlands Environment Assessment Agency (MNP/RIVM), PO Box 303, 3720 BA Bilthoven, Netherlands; Lucas, P.L., Netherlands Environment Assessment Agency (MNP/RIVM), PO Box 303, 3720 BA Bilthoven, Netherlands; den Elzen, M.G.J., Netherlands Environment Assessment Agency (MNP/RIVM), PO Box 303, 3720 BA Bilthoven, Netherlands","This paper presents a set of multi-gas mitigation scenarios that aim for stabilisation of greenhouse gas radiative forcing in 2150 at levels from 3.7 to 5.3 W/m2. At the moment, non-CO2 gasses (methane, nitrous oxide, PFCs, HFCs and SF6) contribute to about a quarter of the global emissions. The analysis shows that including these non-CO2 gases in mitigation analysis is crucial in formulating a cost-effective response. For stabilisation at 4.5 W/m2, a multi-gas approach leads to 40% lower costs than an approach that would focus at CO2- only. Within the assumptions used in this study, the non CO2 gasses contribution to total reduction is very large under less stringent targets (up to 60%), but declines under stringent targets. While stabilising at 3.7 W/m2 obviously leads to larger environmental benefits than the 4.5 W/m2 case (temperature increase in 2100 are 1.9 and 2.3°C, respectively), the costs of the lower target are higher (0.80% and 0.34% of GDP in 2100, respectively). Improving knowledge on how future reduction Potentialfor non-CO2 gasses could develop is shown to be a crucial research question. Copyright © 2006 by the IAEE. All rights reserved.",,,,,,,,"Azar, C., Lindgren, K., Larson, E., Möllersten, K., Carbon capture and storage from fossil fuels and biomass - Costs and potential role in stabilizing the atmosphere Climatic Change, 74 (1-3), pp. 47-79; Criqui, P., (2002) GECS Final Report, , Section 6: Detail report. Grenoble, France: CNRS-IEPE; Criqui, P., Kouvaritakis, N., World energy projections to 2030 (2000) International Journal of Global Energy Issues, 14 (1), pp. 116-136; Cubash, U. and G. A. Meehl (2001). Projections of future climate change. in H. J.T., Y. Ding, D. J. Griggset al. Climate change 2001: The scientific basis. Cambridge: Cambridge University Pressde Vries, H.J.M., van Vuuren, D.P., den Elzen, M.G.J., Janssen, M.A., (2002) The Targets Image Energy model regional (TIMER) - Technical documentation, , Bilthoven, the Netherlands: National Institute of Public Health and the Environment RIVM; DeAngelo, B.J., de la Chesnaye, F.C., Beach, R.H., Sommer, A., Murray, B.C., Methane and Nitrous Oxide Mitigation in Agriculture (2006) Energy Journal, , this issue; Delhotal, K.C., de la Chesnaye, F.C., Gardiner, A., Bates, J., Sankovski, A., Mitigation of Methane and Nitrous Oxide Emissions from Waste, Energy and Industry (2006) Energy Journal, , this issue; den Elzen, M.G.J., Lucas, P., The FAIR model: A tool to analyse environmental and costs implications of climate regimes (2005) Environmental Modeling and Assessment, 10 (2), pp. 115-134; den Elzen, M.G.J., Lucas, P., Van Vuuren, D.P., Abatement costs of post-Kyoto climate regimes (2005) Energy Policy, 33 (16), pp. 2138-2151; den Elzen, M.G.J., Meinshausen, M., (2005) Meeting the EU 2 degree target: Global and regional emission implications, , Bilthoven, The Netherlands: RIVM; Eickhout, B., den Elzen, M.G.J., van Vuuren, D.P., (2003) Multi-gas emission profiles for stabilising greenhouse gas concentrations. Implications of limiting global temper